## SECTION 2: The Ghalibaf-Vahidi power struggle creates an unresolvable negotiation paradox

The assassination of Ali Khamenei on February 28 destroyed Iran's constitutional decision-making architecture. What emerged is a military junta wearing clerical robes, where the people who want peace lack authority and the people with authority want war.

**Ahmad Vahidi** controls the system. His biography reads like a curriculum vitae of the Islamic Republic's most violent operations: Quds Force commander from 1988-1997 (overseeing the 1994 AMIA bombing that killed 85 in Buenos Aires, for which Interpol maintains a Red Notice), defense minister under Ahmadinejad, interior minister during the 2022 Mahsa Amini protest crackdown (sanctioned by the US and EU for directing lethal force), and now IRGC Commander-in-Chief since March 1, replacing the killed Mohammad Pakpour. Vahidi combined intelligence tradecraft, bureaucratic competence, and hardline ideology in a way his predecessors did not. He pushed the Assembly of Experts to immediately install Mojtaba Khamenei as Supreme Leader (alongside IRGC General Jafari and former spy chief Taeb). He compelled Pezeshkian to appoint Zolghadr to replace the assassinated Ali Larijani as SNSC Secretary. He has blocked all civilian intelligence minister appointments, demanding "all critical positions must be decided by the IRGC." Before the Islamabad talks, he declared the missile program a "red line" and reportedly accused Ghalibaf and Araghchi of **"betraying Ali Khamenei"** for sitting down with the US delegation.

The **real power triangle** — Vahidi (IRGC), Zolghadr (SNSC), and Mohsen Rezaei (military adviser to the Supreme Leader) — are all first-generation revolutionaries and IRGC hardliners. As analyst Mousavi Khoeini stated: "Vahidi is in charge of the country. Ghalibaf doesn't have the strength to confront him."

**Ghalibaf operates within an authorization ceiling** that makes deal-delivery structurally impossible under current conditions. Article 176 of Iran's constitution requires Supreme Leader confirmation of all SNSC decisions. Mojtaba Khamenei — elected March 9 after IRGC pressure — has not made a single public appearance, released any audio or video, or been photographed in **over five weeks**. A Times of London intelligence memo reported him "potentially unconscious in Qom." His wife, mother, sister, and brother-in-law were killed in the February 28 strike. Without his constitutional confirmation, no war-and-peace decision has legal force. The confirmation mechanism under Article 176 is **inoperative**.

The Guardian Council's 12 members — all conservative/principlist, effectively appointed through Supreme Leader-controlled channels — have issued no public statement on the command-authority question. The Expediency Discernment Council, chaired by Sadiq Larijani (brother of the assassinated Ali Larijani), attempted to intervene during the succession crisis but lacks military command authority. The Qom seminary has unified behind the war effort: Grand Ayatollahs Makarem Shirazi, Nouri Hamedani, and Kamal al-Haydari all issued fatwas declaring revenge a religious obligation after Khamenei's assassination. The seminary building in Qom was itself struck by Israeli airstrikes, deepening clerical solidarity with the war.

The IRGC's decapitation losses are staggering — approximately **52 senior officials and commanders killed**, including Salami, Pakpour, Bagheri, Hajizadeh, Tangsiri, Larijani, and dozens more. But the IRGC was redesigned in 2008 into 31 provincial corps as "self-contained military nodes" with independent weapons stockpiles, intelligence cells, and pre-delegated command succession spanning three ranks. This architecture was specifically built to survive exactly this scenario.

**KEY FINDINGS:**
- Ghalibaf can negotiate but cannot commit Iran — his signature carries the weight of a parliament speaker in a system where parliament does not control the military
- Vahidi holds effective veto power over any agreement and has publicly framed negotiations as betrayal
- Mojtaba Khamenei's 37-day absence creates a constitutional vacuum that makes ratification of any deal legally impossible
- The IRGC's decentralized structure means even mid-ranking officers can launch independent strikes regardless of what Ghalibaf signs

**PREDICTIVE IMPLICATIONS:** Washington may be negotiating with itself. Any agreement Ghalibaf reaches in Islamabad or elsewhere will be "a political commitment made by a faction whose military wing has already demonstrated that political commitments do not constrain its operational decisions." The only pathway to an implementable deal requires either: (a) economic pain reaching a threshold where the IRGC's own operational capacity is threatened, or (b) Mojtaba Khamenei's emergence with independent authority that an agreement is compatible with regime survival. Neither condition is currently met.

**WATCH INDICATORS:** Any Mojtaba Khamenei public appearance (video, audio, photograph); Vahidi's public statements on negotiations; whether IRGC-affiliated media (Kayhan, Tasnim) endorse or attack future talks; Pezeshkian's statements on economic collapse timeline.

**CONFIDENCE LEVEL:** HIGH on structural constraints; MODERATE on Mojtaba's condition (all sources indirect); LOW on predicting when/if IRGC pain threshold triggers policy change.

