## SECTION 6: The commodity cascade reaches spring planting season at the worst possible moment

The Hormuz closure has created rolling shortages across seven critical commodity categories, each on a different timeline. The most consequential near-term impact is not energy but **fertilizer** — its disruption during the narrow spring planting window locks in food price increases for 12-18 months.

**Urea and ammonia fertilizer** represent the sharpest near-term vulnerability. **46% of globally traded urea** and 25% of ammonia originate from Gulf countries. QatarEnergy halted urea production after suspending LNG operations. FOB granular urea prices have surged 50% to ~$720/mt. No strategic fertilizer reserves exist anywhere. The critical fact: the US **Corn Belt nitrogen application window is mid-April through early May — we are in it now.** Farmers unable to secure nitrogen are switching from corn to soybeans, reducing corn supply. This decision, once made, locks in reduced corn acreage for the 2026 harvest, driving up feed costs for beef, poultry, and dairy for the next 12 months.

**Helium** is approaching a physical cliff. Qatar produces 33% of global supply, and Ras Laffan sustained "extensive" damage requiring years to repair. The overlooked detail: specialized cryogenic helium containers can only store liquid helium for **35-48 days** before it evaporates through pressure-release valves. Containers filled around February 28 are now reaching this limit (day 46-47). Some 200 containers worth $1 million each are stranded in the Middle East. South Korea imports 65% of its helium from Qatar; Samsung and SK Hynix have months of inventory but face an approaching wall. MRI scanners in hospitals worldwide still rely on liquid helium — rationing has begun, with scheduling delays expected within weeks.

**LNG** creates a European crisis with a specific calendar. Storage sits at approximately **29-30% capacity** — historically low — against an EU mandate requiring 90% by November 1. The refill gap of ~60 bcm at current prices could cost over **€100 billion**. The last LNG tanker from Qatar arrived in the UK on April 10. No more Qatar LNG is reaching Europe. Shell CEO warned Europe could face fuel shortages by April. US LNG exports set records in March, but American capacity cannot replace Gulf supply.

**Aluminum** smelter shutdowns are potentially irreversible. When molten aluminum smelting pots "freeze" — as occurred at EGA facilities in the UAE after missile strikes — the damage takes **years to repair**. LME prices hit 4-year highs of $3,571/t, with US Midwest premiums at record $1.10/lb. Critically, **58% of LME warranted stocks are Russian aluminum**, inaccessible to Western buyers, meaning effective available inventory is far lower than headline figures suggest.

**Jet fuel** creates the most immediately visible European consumer impact. **40% of Europe's jet fuel supply** passes through Hormuz. Most EU airports have only **8-10 days of reserves**. ACI Europe warned of systemic shortage within three weeks as of late March. SAS cancelled 1,000 flights in April; Ryanair warned of summer capacity cuts; Wizz Air reported a €50 million profit hit. European tourism — €851 billion annually supporting 14 million jobs — faces material disruption by June.

**Week-by-week consumer impact calendar (assuming 95% disruption continues):** Week 1-2 (April 15-28): US diesel surcharges on all carriers; fertilizer unavailability forces Corn Belt planting decisions; European jet fuel allocations begin at airports. Week 3-4 (April 29-May 12): Corn planting window closes with reduced nitrogen; plastic packaging cost increases hit grocery shelves; helium rationing reaches US hospitals. Week 5-6 (May 13-26): Reduced corn acreage locked in; airline fuel surcharges of $50-150/ticket; beef/poultry price warnings. Week 7-8 (May 27-June 9): Grocery prices elevated 10-15% for meat; European summer flight capacity down 15-25%; semiconductor supply chain stress visible in extended lead times.

**KEY FINDINGS:**
- Fertilizer disruption during the two-week spring planting window (now through early May) locks in food price increases for 12-18 months regardless of when Hormuz reopens
- Helium containers stranded in the Gulf are reaching their 35-48 day evaporation limit right now — physical shortage is imminent, not projected
- European jet fuel reserves of 8-10 days make aviation the first major consumer-facing disruption in Europe
- Aluminum smelter freezing creates potentially irreversible production losses measured in years

**PREDICTIVE IMPLICATIONS:** Even an immediate ceasefire and Hormuz reopening cannot prevent the fertilizer-driven food price increases already locked in by missed planting windows. The political consequences of $5+ grocery inflation will manifest in Q4 2026 — perfectly timed for November midterms. This timeline creates powerful incentive for both parties to assign blame.

**WATCH INDICATORS:** USDA planted acreage report (June); helium spot prices and hospital rationing reports; European airport fuel allocation announcements; LME aluminum warrant drawdowns (excluding Russian metal); TTF natural gas prices vs. €50/MWh threshold.

**CONFIDENCE LEVEL:** HIGH on fertilizer timing and locked-in impact; HIGH on helium container physics; MODERATE on exact shortage timelines (depend on inventory drawdown rates that vary by country); LOW on precise consumer price impact magnitudes.

